Cell[TextData[{
 "The plot of this function in Figure 15 shows something rather surprising.   \
The optimal proportion ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["q", "*"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " does not sink below 1 = 100% until the risk aversion becomes about 17 or \
greater.  (Try zooming in on the graph to find more precisely where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["q", "*"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " intersects the horizontal line through 1.)  There are two ways to make \
sense of this: investors whose risk aversions are less than 17 hold all of \
their wealth in the stock and none in the bond, or if it is possible to \
borrow cash (which is called holding a ",
 StyleBox["short position",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " in the bond), then an investor with low risk aversion borrows an amount ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"|", 
    RowBox[{"1", "-", 
     SuperscriptBox["q", "*"]}], "|", "W"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 " of cash and places his original wealth plus this borrowed amount in the \
stock.  His overall wealth is still ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["W", TraditionalForm]]],
 ", because he owns ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"W", "+", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["q", "*"], "-", "1"}], ")"}], "W"}]}], 
   TraditionalForm]]],
 " of stock and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"-", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["q", "*"], "-", "1"}], ")"}]}], "W"}], 
   TraditionalForm]]],
 " of cash.  He hopes that the stock grows enough to let him pay off his cash \
debt, and still profit by the growth of his holding in stock.  "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.432995130736*^9, 3.432995131814*^9}, {3.434725432866*^9,
   3.4347254331470003`*^9}}],

