Cell[TextData[{
 "\tThis chapter has only scratched the surface of the many interesting \
extensions and applications of probability.  Other important areas, such as \
reliability theory, stochastic optimization, information theory, the analysis \
of algorithms, and inventory theory, await you.  Or, you might decide you \
want to study Markov chains, ",
 StyleBox["Brownian motion",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 " and other random processes, queues, or finance more deeply.  Probably the \
most important next step is the subject of statistics, which we have \
previewed a number of times.  It is my hope that your experience with this \
book has prepared you well for all of these studies, as well as enhancing \
your problem-solving abilities, and giving you a new view of a world fraught \
with uncertainties. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.432996951876*^9, 3.4329969551400003`*^9}, {
  3.4571856801006002`*^9, 3.4571856854046*^9}}],

Cell["Exercises 6.5", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.4329945329309998`*^9, 3.4329945340550003`*^9}, {
  3.433019854191318*^9, 3.4330198554583178`*^9}},
 TextAlignment->Center,
 FontWeight->"Bold"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "1.  If your investment strategy is to pick just one stock from among the \
following three to invest in, and your risk aversion is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"a", "=", "5"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", which stock would you pick?\n\tStock 1: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Mu]", "1"], "=", ".05"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{
     SuperscriptBox[
      SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "1"], "2"], "=", ".008"}]}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ";  Stock 2: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Mu]", "2"], "=", ".06"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{
     SuperscriptBox[
      SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "1"], "2"], "=", ".01"}]}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ";  Stock 3: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Mu]", "1"], "=", ".09"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{
     SuperscriptBox[
      SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "1"], "2"], "=", ".02"}]}], TraditionalForm]]]
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "2.  Find the optimal portfolio of one stock and one bond for an investor \
with risk aversion ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"a", "=", "12"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", if the non-risky rate of return is 4%, and the stock rate of return is \
random with mean 5% and standard deviation 4%.  "
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "3.  (",
 StyleBox["Mathematica",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ") Simulate the total returns for 200 replications of the investment problem \
in Exercise 2, for the optimal portfolio, for a portfolio consisting of 100% \
stock, and for a portfolio consisting of 50% stock and 50% bonds.  Assume an \
initial wealth of $1000, and assume that the stock rate of return is normally \
distributed.  Produce and compare histograms and summary statistics of the \
simulated returns.  "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.433082326778*^9, 3.433082347351*^9}, 
   3.4571857007706003`*^9}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "4.  Suppose that two independent stocks with mean rates of return ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Mu]", "1"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Mu]", "2"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " and standard deviations ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "1"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "2"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " are available, as well as the non-risky bond with rate of return ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["r", TraditionalForm]]],
 ". Find expressions for the optimal proportions of wealth that an investor \
with risk aversion ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["a", TraditionalForm]]],
 " is to hold in each asset.  Does the relative balance between the two risky \
assets depend on the risk aversion?"
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "5.  Suppose that the non-risky rate of return is 5%, and we are interested \
in a two period portfolio problem in which we collect our profit at the end \
of the second time period.  If the stock follows a binomial model as \
described in the second subsection, with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"b", "=", ".10"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ",",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{" ", 
    RowBox[{"a", "=", "0"}]}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"p", "=", ".4"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", and the investor's risk aversion is 15, find the optimal portfolio."
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "6.  (",
 StyleBox["Mathematica",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ") In Example 2, produce a graph of the option price at time 0 as a function \
of the exercise time ",
 StyleBox["T",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", with the initial stock price = $14, and other parameters as in the \
example:  ",
 StyleBox["E ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "= 18, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"b", "=", ".09"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"a", "=", ".03"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"r", "=", ".05"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ".  Then see how the graph changes as you vary the initial stock price."
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "7.  A stock follows the binomial model with initial price $30, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"b", "=", ".08"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"a", "=", "0"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", and the riskless rate is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"r", "=", ".04"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ".  Find (by hand) the probability ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["p", TraditionalForm]]],
 ", the distribution of the stock price two time units later, and the value \
of an option whose exercise time is 2 and whose exercise price is $32. "
}], "Text"],

Cell["\<\
8.  Express the value of the European call option (10) in terms of the \
binomial cumulative distribution function.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "9.  An ",
 StyleBox["American call option",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " is one that can be exercised at any time prior to the termination time ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["T", TraditionalForm]]],
 " of the contract.  Argue that a lower bound for the value of an American \
call option ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"V", "(", 
    RowBox[{"S", ",", "t", ",", "E"}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 " is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"max", "(", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"S", "-", "E"}], ",", "0"}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ".  Sketch the graph of this lower bound as a function of ",
 StyleBox["S",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ".  (Incidentally, it can be shown that the value of an American call is the \
same as that of a European call.  So this lower bound holds for the European \
call option as well.)"
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "10.  Consider a single time period option ",
 StyleBox["problem ",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 "with a general binomial model expressed by (8) holding for the stock upon \
which the option is based.  Again let ",
 StyleBox["r",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " be the non-risky rate.  Show that the investment action of holding one \
option at time 0 can be ",
 StyleBox["replicated",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " by holding a certain number ",
 StyleBox["N",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " of shares of the stock, and borrowing an amount ",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " at the non-risky rate, i.e., whether the stock goes up or down in the \
single time period, this replicating portfolio performs exactly as the option \
would perform.  Find expressions for the ",
 StyleBox["N",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " that do this replication."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.432997100401*^9, 3.4329971012390003`*^9}, 
   3.433019873242318*^9}],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["11. In the context of options pricing it was claimed in the \
section that opportunities for limitless risk-free profits could ensue if the \
anti-arbitrage condition ",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"a", "<", "r", "<", "b"}], TraditionalForm]],
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 StyleBox[" was not in force, where",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 StyleBox[" ",
  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["r", TraditionalForm]]],
 " is the interest rate on a risk-free asset and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["a", TraditionalForm]]],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["b", TraditionalForm]]],
 " are the parameters in formula (8) governing the possible states of the \
risky asset. Explain how this can happen. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.43299628037*^9, 3.43299629204*^9}, {3.432997141778*^9, 
  3.432997142572*^9}, {3.4330680676077194`*^9, 3.4330682399757195`*^9}}],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["12.  The perception of a firm's value by its stockholders and \
potential stockholders is an influential factor in the price of a share of \
its stock on the market. There have been several models put forth by finance \
specialists for the value of a firm, but a relatively simple one involves the \
present value of the expected total profit.  Consider a firm whose profits \
last year were $40 million.  They are expected to grow each year by a random \
factor ",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"1", "+", 
    SubscriptBox["X", "i"]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 StyleBox[", where ",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["X", "i"], TraditionalForm]],
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 StyleBox[" is normally distributed with mean .04 and variance .0004. Assume \
that these random variables are independent of each other. Suppose that the \
value of money discounts by a percentage of ",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"r", "=", ".02"}], TraditionalForm]],
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 StyleBox[" per year.  Compute the present value of the expected total profit \
through year 10.  ",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]]
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.4329946617679996`*^9, 3.432994672148*^9}, {
   3.4329971446879997`*^9, 3.432997145737*^9}, {3.433084017413*^9, 
   3.433084181205*^9}, {3.4330844310559998`*^9, 3.433084626178*^9}, {
   3.433084689101*^9, 3.433084730466*^9}, {3.433084773869*^9, 
   3.433084791995*^9}, {3.433085013032*^9, 3.433085030784*^9}, 
   3.4331526616363173`*^9},
 FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["13. (",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 StyleBox["Mathematica",
  FontSlant->"Italic",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 StyleBox[") A man is planning to retire in two years, at which time he will \
have saved an amount ",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["W", TraditionalForm]],
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 StyleBox[" in his retirement account.  Suppose that he is allowed to lock in \
the interest rate ",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["R", TraditionalForm]],
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 StyleBox[" on his retirement account at the time of retirement, but ",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["R", TraditionalForm]],
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 StyleBox[" is unknown to him now. He estimates that ",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["R", TraditionalForm]],
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 StyleBox[" is normally distributed with mean .035 and variance .000095. He \
would like to be able to consume a fixed income of at least $50,000 for at \
least 20 years. How large must ",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["W", TraditionalForm]],
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 StyleBox[" be in order for him to achieve his financial goal with \
probability at least .9?",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]]
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.432994768666*^9, 3.4329947944630003`*^9}, {
   3.432997147426*^9, 3.432997148675*^9}, {3.433084866961*^9, 
   3.433084984117*^9}, {3.433085041252*^9, 3.433085190113*^9}, {
   3.433152665308317*^9, 3.4331526666293173`*^9}, {3.433153839619317*^9, 
   3.4331538720123167`*^9}, {3.433153906666317*^9, 3.433153976775317*^9}, 
   3.433154558723317*^9},
 FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]
}, Open  ]]
